    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        ☿ si die cu[m] diurnus et nocte cu[m] nocturnis planetis [imagitur] bene est, co[n]tra eu[m] pessimu[m] est. <!--JG: Unsure abt 'imagitur'-->
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <symbol_in_text name="Mercury"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Mercury, it is well if [...] on the day when by day and by night with the nocturnal planets, it is most disloyal against him. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        At nox est: vide igitur quid infine capitis pra[e]redentis dixisti <!-- FSF: not sure about infine -->
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                But it was night. Therefore, see what [...] you said in the preceding chapters.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        no[n] partiter 
